00:15:32,370 --> 00:15:37,150
But I think as the Chinese Communist Party looks

248
00:15:37,150 --> 00:15:39,920
at that history in the former Soviet Union,

249
00:15:39,920 --> 00:15:46,350
it views that denunciation of Stalin as a critical turning point

250
00:15:46,350 --> 00:15:51,800
that delegitimized the Communist Party of the Soviet Union.

251
00:15:51,800 --> 00:15:55,500
And it has made a clear determination that it

252
00:15:55,500 --> 00:15:58,080
doesn't want to go down that path.

253
00:15:58,080 --> 00:16:03,270
So I really don't think we're going to get the kind of open history

254
00:16:03,270 --> 00:16:06,930
that you're talking about until the party is gone,

255
00:16:06,930 --> 00:16:10,550
or at least gone as being the only party in town.

256
00:16:10,550 --> 00:16:13,840
That's not to say that there isn't amazing scholarship being

257
00:16:13,840 --> 00:16:18,040
done by some very talented historians in the PRC today,

258
00:16:18,040 --> 00:16:22,770
who are doing everything they can to push the envelope, who have access

259
00:16:22,770 --> 00:16:28,830
to archival materials that were unavailable in previous years,

260
00:16:28,830 --> 00:16:33,150
and who are using those archives and often oral histories

261
00:16:33,150 --> 00:16:38,820
and a whole variety of other sources to try to write as boldly as they can

262
00:16:38,820 --> 00:16:42,210
about the history of the PRC.

263
00:16:42,210 --> 00:16:45,500
But I don't really think that their work is

264
00:16:45,500 --> 00:16:50,530
going to play a major role in delegitimizing the party because I

265
00:16:50,530 --> 00:16:55,940
think the party will maintain a very tight control over the publication

266
00:16:55,940 --> 00:16:59,620
of those kinds of materials.

